<B><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE=5><P ALIGN="CENTER">Algebraic Series Learning Plan 1</P>
<P ALIGN="CENTER">Arithmetic Series</P>
</FONT><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE=4><P ALIGN="CENTER"></P>
</B></FONT><FONT FACE="Arial"><P>While working through this plan you should be referring to your lecture notes titled ‘Arithmetic Progressions’.</P>

<P>Sometimes we are interested not with a single number, but with a series of observations.   We might be interested in how the sales made by a company has changed over some period.   The monthly sales figures ( in thousands of £) may form a sequence of numbers, like:</P>

<P ALIGN="CENTER">21, 24, 26, 32, 37, 45, 49,</P>
<P ALIGN="CENTER"></P>
<P>This is a sequence of numbers.   If the numbers in the sequence follow some distinct pattern, they are called a series (or progression).</P>

<P>One of the main types of series is:</P>

<B><P>Arithmetic Series (Progression)</P>

</B><P>In an arithmetic series each number is larger (or smaller) than the previous number by a fixed amount e.g.</P>

<P ALIGN="CENTER">12, 17, 22, 27, 32,…….</P>
<P ALIGN="CENTER"></P>
<P>The initial term is labelled a, here a = 12 and the common difference between the terms is d, here d = 5. </P>

<P>Consider the arithmetic series</P>

<P ALIGN="CENTER">10, 8, 6, 4, 2, 0, -2, -4 …..</P>
<P ALIGN="CENTER"></P>
<P>Here a = 10 and d= -2.</P>

<B><P>nth term</P>
</B>
<P>As stated above, the initial term is a and the common difference between terms is d.   Furthermore the number of terms in the series is denoted n and the nth term in the series by t<SUB>n</SUB>.   (Sometimes u<SUB>n</SUB> is used to denote the nth term.)</P>

<P>In general an arithmetic series can be described as,</P>

<P>a,   a+ d,   a + 2d,   a + 3d,…….. hence the nth term, <B>t<SUB>n</SUB> = a + (n-1)d</B>.</P>

<B><P>Example</P>

</B><P>Reconsider the series above</P>

<P ALIGN="CENTER">12, 17, 22, 27, 32,…….</P>
<P>Here a = 12 and d= 5.   We know t<SUB>3</SUB>, the third term, is 22.   Check using the formula.</P>

<P ALIGN="CENTER">t<SUB>n</SUB> = a + (n -1)d</P>
<P ALIGN="CENTER"><FONT FACE="Symbol">&#222;</FONT>
 t<SUB>3</SUB> = 12 + (3 -1)5</P>
<P ALIGN="CENTER"><FONT FACE="Symbol">&#222;</FONT>
 t<SUB>3</SUB> = 12 + 10</P>
<P ALIGN="CENTER"><FONT FACE="Symbol">&#222;</FONT>
t<SUB>3</SUB> = 22 as expected</P>

<P>Using this formula means we can calculate the value of any term without having to evaluate all the previous ones.</P>
<B>
</B><P>Read pages 1 and 2 of your notes.  </P>
<B>
<P>Sum of n terms</P>
</B>
<P>It is often useful to be able to find the total of a number of terms e.g the sum of the first four terms of the series above is </P>

<P ALIGN="CENTER">12 + 17 + 22 + 27 = 78</P>
<P ALIGN="CENTER"></P>
<P>It can be shown that the sum of the first n terms of an arithmetic series is:</P>

<B><P ALIGN="CENTER">S<SUB>n </SUB>= n/2(2a + (n-1)d)</P>

</B><P>Check using this formula that the sum of the first four terms above is in fact 78. </P>

<P>n = 4, a = 12 and d= 5</P>

<B><P ALIGN="CENTER">S<SUB>n </SUB>= n/2(2a + (n-1)d)</P>
</B><P ALIGN="CENTER"><FONT FACE="Symbol">&#222;</FONT>
 S<SUB>4</SUB> = 4/2(2(12) + (4 -1)5)</P>
<P ALIGN="CENTER"><FONT FACE="Symbol">&#222;</FONT>
 S<SUB>4</SUB> = 2( 24 + 15)</P>
<P ALIGN="CENTER"><FONT FACE="Symbol">&#222;</FONT>
 S<SUB>4</SUB> = 78 as expected</P>

<P>Work through <a href="runcal.htm#==k:\calmat\tcrun.exe calpopup //?~ 0 3 1 d~?">3-1 section d</a> and <a href="runcal.htm#==k:\calmat\tcrun.exe calpopup //?~ 0 3 1 e~?">section e</a>.   Read pages 3 – 6 of your notes.   Try <a href="launch.htm#q0208">q0208</a>, <a href="launch.htm#q0188">q0188</a> and <a href="launch.htm#q0187">q0187</a>.</P>

<B><P>Example</P>
</B>
<P>On joining my company 6 years ago my contract stated my initial salary would be £17,000 with an annual increment of £800.</P>

<OL TYPE="i">

<LI>Calculate my salary at present.</LI>
<LI>How much have I earned in total over my 6 years employment ?</LI></OL>

<br>
<P>(i) My salary is an arithmetic series with a = 17,000 and d = 800. Salary in the nth year is calculate as t<SUB>n</SUB> = a + (n -1)d.</P>

<P>Hence t<SUB>6</SUB> = 17000 + (6 -1)(800)</P>
<P><FONT FACE="Symbol">&#222;</FONT>
 t<SUB>6 </SUB>= 17000 + 4000</P>
<P> <FONT FACE="Symbol">&#222;</FONT>
 t<SUB>6</SUB> = 21000</P>

<P>My salary at present is £21,000.</P>

<P>(ii) My total salary over n years is S<SUB>n </SUB>= n/2(2a + (n-1)d).</P>

<P>Hence S<SUB>6</SUB> = 6/2(2(17000) + (6 – 1)(800))</P>
<P><FONT FACE="Symbol">&#222;</FONT>
 S<SUB>6</SUB> = 3(34000 + 4000)</P>
<P><FONT FACE="Symbol">&#222;</FONT>
S<SUB>6</SUB> = 114000</P>

<P>Over my 6 years employment I have earned £114,000.</P>
